  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (US)\n- First international recognition of money laundering as a financial crime\n- Introduced reporting requirements for financial institutions\n\n2. 1980s Developments\n- Growing awareness of drug-related money laundering\n- Introduction of international anti-money laundering (AML) frameworks\n- Enhanced financial tracking mechanisms\n\n3. Key Milestones\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- 1990: Expanded international cooperation\n- Standardized global anti-money laundering regulations\n\n4. Post-9/11 Legislation\n- Patriot Act (2001)\n- Increased focus on terrorism financing\n- Stricter customer identification requirements\n- Enhanced information sharing between agencies\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Broader definition of financial crimes\n- Increased penalties and enforcement\n- More comprehensive beneficial ownership disclosure\n\n6. Global Compliance\n- Mandatory Know Your Customer (KYC) procedures\n- Risk-based approach to financial investigations\n- Continuous technological adaptation\n- Cross-border information exchange\n\nThe legislative landscape continues to evolve with emerging financial technologies and global economic challenges.",
